<paragraph id="D44236A4FF83FFAAFF27FD6EFA1FFC8D" blockId="3.[151,1436,725,953]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<keyLead id="6F0C9591FF83FFAAFF27FD6EFA1FFC8D" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
1 Extreme base of cerci subequal in width to the space between them (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFCC2FD6EFC27FD6F" box="[882,941,725,747]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[312,1283,1193,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[312,1283,1193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 7. Perigomphus basicornis sp. nov., holotype ♂. 4) Dorsal view of S 9 – 10 showing the caudal appendages. 5) Left latero-dorsal view of caudal appendages. 6) Left lateral view (slightly ventral) of caudal appendages. 7) S 8 – 10 and caudal appendages, ventral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ah = anterior hamuli, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Ph = posterior hamulus. Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, sbvh = sub-basal ventral horn of cerci." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832660/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); mesal carinate margin of cerci entire, not notched subapically (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFEEBFD48FE3FFC8D" box="[347,437,755,777]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1918,1941]" captionTargetBox="[312,1283,1193,1901]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[312,1283,1193,1901]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 7. Perigomphus basicornis sp. nov., holotype ♂. 4) Dorsal view of S 9 – 10 showing the caudal appendages. 5) Left latero-dorsal view of caudal appendages. 6) Left lateral view (slightly ventral) of caudal appendages. 7) S 8 – 10 and caudal appendages, ventral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ah = anterior hamuli, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Ph = posterior hamulus. Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, sbvh = sub-basal ventral horn of cerci." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832660/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Figs. 4, 5</figureCitation>
)......................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="13FD4D27FF83FFAAFA81FD48FA1FFC8D" authorityName="Amaya-Vallejo &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez &amp; Realpe" authorityYear="2017" box="[1329,1429,755,777]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Perigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basicornis">
<emphasis id="E689EAB6FF83FFAAFA81FD48FA1FFC8D" box="[1329,1429,755,777]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">basicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44236A4FF83FFAAFF27FCABFA11FCC7" blockId="3.[151,1436,725,953]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<keyLead id="6F0C9591FF83FFAAFF27FCABFA11FCC7" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<emphasis id="E689EAB6FF83FFAAFF27FCABFF15FCA2" bold="true" box="[151,159,784,806]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">-</emphasis>
Extreme base of cerci notoriously shorter than space between them; mesal carinate margin of cerci notched subapically (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFADBFCABFE98FCC7" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[214,1371,264,1557]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,235,1596]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Perigomphus spp. 8) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. angularis; 9) the same, lateral view; 10) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. pallidistylus; 11) the same, lateral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, ma = medial angle, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, san = subapical notch, sbvp = sub-basal ventral projection of cerci. Figs. 8 – 9 after Tennessen (2011); Figs. 10 – 11 after Belle (1972)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832662/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Figs. 8, 10</figureCitation>
)............................................................................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="6F092E01FF83FFAAFF27FCF0FA10FC3D" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<paragraph id="D44236A4FF83FFAAFF27FCF0FA11FCFA" blockId="3.[151,1436,725,953]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<keyLead id="6F0C9591FF83FFAAFF27FCF0FA11FCFA" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
2 Cerci in dorsal view with the medial angle at extreme base projected toward midline and almost meeting that of opposite in each cercus (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFEEDFCD3FE1DFCFA" box="[349,407,872,894]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[214,1371,264,1557]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,235,1596]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Perigomphus spp. 8) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. angularis; 9) the same, lateral view; 10) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. pallidistylus; 11) the same, lateral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, ma = medial angle, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, san = subapical notch, sbvp = sub-basal ventral projection of cerci. Figs. 8 – 9 after Tennessen (2011); Figs. 10 – 11 after Belle (1972)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832662/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFDF0FCD3FDF0FCFA" box="[576,634,872,894]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[214,1371,264,1557]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,235,1596]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Perigomphus spp. 8) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. angularis; 9) the same, lateral view; 10) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. pallidistylus; 11) the same, lateral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, ma = medial angle, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, san = subapical notch, sbvp = sub-basal ventral projection of cerci. Figs. 8 – 9 after Tennessen (2011); Figs. 10 – 11 after Belle (1972)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832662/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) with a vestigial sub-basal projection............................. 
<taxonomicName id="13FD4D27FF83FFAAFA8FFCD3FA11FCFA" authorityName="Tennessen" authorityYear="2011" box="[1343,1435,872,894]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Perigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angularis">
<emphasis id="E689EAB6FF83FFAAFA8FFCD3FA11FCFA" box="[1343,1435,872,894]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">angularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D44236A4FF83FFAAFF27FC3DFA10FC3D" blockId="3.[151,1436,725,953]" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
<keyLead id="6F0C9591FF83FFAAFF27FC3DFA10FC3D" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">
- Cerci in dorsal view (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFE01FC3EFE7DFC1F" box="[433,503,901,923]" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[214,1371,264,1557]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,235,1596]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Perigomphus spp. 8) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. angularis; 9) the same, lateral view; 10) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. pallidistylus; 11) the same, lateral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, ma = medial angle, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, san = subapical notch, sbvp = sub-basal ventral projection of cerci. Figs. 8 – 9 after Tennessen (2011); Figs. 10 – 11 after Belle (1972)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832662/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
) with the medial margin at extreme base undeveloped and slightly undulate; in lateral view (
<figureCitation id="4CC62A21FF83FFAAFAC5FC3EFF73FC3D" captionStart="FIGURES 8 – 11" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1664,1687]" captionTargetBox="[214,1371,264,1557]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,235,1596]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8 – 11. Perigomphus spp. 8) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. angularis; 9) the same, lateral view; 10) Dorsal view of S 10 and caudal appendages of male of P. pallidistylus; 11) the same, lateral view. a = arm of epiproct, Ce = cerci, Ep = epiproct, ma = medial angle, p = baso-lateral process of cerci, Pr = dorsolateral process of paraproct, san = subapical notch, sbvp = sub-basal ventral projection of cerci. Figs. 8 – 9 after Tennessen (2011); Figs. 10 – 11 after Belle (1972)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/832662/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) with a well-developed sub-basal projection..................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="13FD4D27FF83FFAAFA95FC18FA10FC3D" authorityName="Belle" authorityYear="1972" box="[1317,1434,931,953]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Perigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="3" pageNumber="398" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallidistylus">
<emphasis id="E689EAB6FF83FFAAFA95FC18FA10FC3D" box="[1317,1434,931,953]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="398">pallidistylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
